(86) Relation to Religion.

After considering the relations of Lucan to contemporary philosophy it may not be out of place to add a few words on the religions of the age and his references to them.

(a) The break-up of the old Roman beliefs in the latter days of the Republic was followed by the great statedirected revival under Augustus In its outward observances the national religion, a medley of indigenous and imported elements, was to a remarkable extent restored. But the ancient faiths‚ if they had ever exercised a sway over men’s minds and controlled their lives, had long lost this power and could never recover it again. Not only had Greek speculation destroyed the intellectuat basis of belief, but the characters attributed to the gods¹⁷ served to disgust the good and fumished an excuse, if such were needed, to the votaries of vice and crime.

No wonder then that Roman society turned to the East and to the West for the satisfaction of its emotional or quasi-spiritual needs. Under the Roman tolerance of alien worships‚ only interrupted now and then for reasons of state, new gods and new systems of religion were mou domiciled in the great city. From Syria and Asia Minor and above all from Egypt came the Oriental cults of excitement and mystery, rrirh their orgies initiations mutilations and symbolisms: and crowds rere drawn after them.
